":"1237","about 1108":"about 1108","1200":"1200","1078":"1078","from 1153 to 1160":"from 1153 to 1160","1108":"1108","Nesle, Somme, Picardie, France":"Nesle, Somme, Picardie, France","Nesle, Hauts-de-France":"Péronne, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Brugges, French Flanders":"Brugge, West Flanders, Belgium","Nesle, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Kingdom of France":"Nesle, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Nesle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Horst.","German: from a pet form of the female medieval personal name <i>Nes</i>, a short form of   Agnes  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Agnes","meanings":["English; French (<b>Agnès</b>); Hungarian (<b>Ágnes</b>): from a female personal name, which is from Late Latin <i>Agnes</i> and this one from Greek <i>Hagnē</i>, from <i>hagnē</i> ‘pure, chaste’. Saint Agnes was a Christian virgin martyr, one of those who suffered under the persecutions of Diocletian in 303  AD . Her name was associated by folk etymology with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, and in medieval art she is often depicted with a lamb (the lamb of God). See also English   Annis  .","American shortened (and altered) form of rare Greek metronymics <b>Agnidis</b> or <